\subsection{Variance vs Performance}
We observe a strong negative correlation between inter-layer variance and model accuracy
(Pearson $r \approx -0.92$). Models with lower variance exhibit more uniform recurrence
structure across layers, suggesting that consistency in representation geometry is associated
with improved generalization performance.

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{figure3_variance_vs_accuracy.png}
	\caption{
		Inter-layer variance versus test accuracy across trained models.
		A strong negative correlation is observed ($r \approx -0.92$), indicating that
		more coherent layer-wise representations (lower variance) correspond to higher performance.
	}
	\label{fig:variance_accuracy}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Operator Sensitivity via Lambda Sweep}
The $\lambda$-sweep reveals a sharp transition in determinism near $\lambda = 0$,
corresponding to the shift from linear to nonlinear operator regimes.
This behavior is consistent across layers and indicates that recurrence structure
is highly sensitive to even small nonlinear transformations.

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{figure4_lambda_sweep.png}
	\caption{
		Determinism (DET) as a function of operator strength $\lambda$ for each layer.
		A sharp transition occurs near $\lambda \approx 0$, indicating high sensitivity
		to the introduction of nonlinearity.
	}
	\label{fig:lambda_sweep}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Operator Comparison}
Operator choice significantly impacts both recurrence structure and performance.
Smooth, saturating operators such as $\tanh$ achieve the highest accuracy,
while non-saturating or non-smooth operators exhibit reduced performance and higher variance.
This supports the hypothesis that operator-induced recurrence structure enhances observability.

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{figure5_operator_comparison.png}
	\caption{
		Comparison of model accuracy across different operators.
		Smooth, saturating nonlinearities (tanh, sigmoid) outperform non-saturating
		or non-smooth operators (ReLU, clipping).
	}
	\label{fig:operator_comparison}
\end{figure}

\begin{table}[H]
	\centering
	\begin{tabular}{lcc}
		\toprule
		Operator & Accuracy & Variance             \\
		\midrule
		tanh     & 0.91     & $4.1 \times 10^{-5}$ \\
		sigmoid  & 0.89     & $5.5 \times 10^{-5}$ \\
		GELU     & 0.895    & $5.0 \times 10^{-5}$ \\
