\subsection{Coherence–Fertility Relationship}
We observe a strong positive relationship between Fertility (F) and Coherence (C),
with a logarithmic functional form:
\[
	C = a \log(F) + b
\]
indicating diminishing returns. Early increases in recurrence structure yield
substantial gains in coherence, while later increases produce smaller effects.

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{figure6_cf_relationship.png}
	\caption{
		Relationship between Coherence (C) and Fertility (F).
		The dashed line shows a logarithmic fit $C = a \log(F) + b$,
		indicating diminishing returns as recurrence structure increases.
	}
	\label{fig:cf_relationship}
\end{figure}
\[
	C = a \log(F) + b
\]
with $a=2.71$, $b=0.97$, $R^2=0.82$.

\subsection{Operator Non-Invariance}

We tested whether Fertility (F) is invariant under operator transformations.
We find that model rankings are not preserved across operators:

\begin{itemize}
	\item Identity vs $\tanh$: $r \approx 0.05$
	\item Identity vs sigmoid: $r \approx 0.43$
	\item Linear-like operators (identity, ReLU) remain correlated ($r \approx 1.0$)
\end{itemize}

This demonstrates that $F$ is operator-dependent and not a coordinate-invariant quantity.
However, restricted invariance holds within a class of linear-like operators, suggesting the existence of operator equivalence classes.

This negative result indicates that $\Phi$ captures observer-dependent structure rather than intrinsic system invariants.

\subsection{Statistical Validation}

All correlations were evaluated using both Pearson and Spearman coefficients.
Confidence intervals were estimated via bootstrapping with 1000 resamples.

Key results:
\begin{itemize}
	\item $r(F, \text{accuracy}) \approx 0.93$
	\item $r(C, F) \approx 0.90$
	\item $r(\text{variance}, \text{accuracy}) \approx -0.92$
\end{itemize}

All reported correlations are statistically significant ($p < 0.01$).

\subsection{Extended Model}

To account for residual structure, we model Coherence as:

\[
	C = a \log(F) + b_1 \mathrm{Sat} + b_2 \mathrm{Smooth} + b_3 \mathrm{Curv} + b
\]

Fitted coefficients:
\begin{itemize}
	\item $a = 49687.7$
	\item $b_1 = 1751.6$ (saturation)
	\item $b_2 = -935.8$ (smoothness)
	\item $b_3 = 9269.7$ (curvature)
	\item $b = -10243.9$
\end{itemize}

This model achieves $R^2 \approx 0.93$, improving over the logarithmic model ($R^2 \approx 0.82$).

\section{Statistical Analysis}

\begin{itemize}
	\item Pearson and Spearman correlations computed
	\item Confidence intervals via bootstrapping (n=1000)
	\item All reported correlations significant ($p<0.01$)
\end{itemize}

\section{Ablation Studies}

We performed targeted ablation studies to isolate the contribution of key components:

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Operator Ablation:} Removing nonlinear operators collapses $\Phi$ structure and eliminates layer separability.
	\item \textbf{Random Control:} Untrained networks exhibit unstable scaling behavior and higher variance, confirming that learned structure stabilizes recurrence geometry.
	\item \textbf{Fertility Decoupling:} Holding model weights fixed while varying operators changes $F$ without affecting accuracy, demonstrating that $F$ is measurement-dependent.
	\item \textbf{Variance Regularization:} Directly minimizing inter-layer variance improves accuracy by up to 2\%.
\end{itemize}

These results confirm that recurrence structure, not operator nonlinearity alone, drives observability.

\section{Discussion}

A key implication of these results is that representation structure is not
an intrinsic property of the system alone but depends on the interaction
between system and observation operator. This has consequences for common
analysis methods, which implicitly assume operator invariance.

Furthermore, the decomposition into Fertility and Coherence reveals that
performance is driven primarily by total recurrence structure (F),
while inter-layer consistency (C) follows as a secondary effect with
diminishing returns. This suggests a hierarchical organization of
representation quality.

The dependence on operator properties (saturation, smoothness, curvature)
indicates that observability can be modulated systematically, opening
the possibility of designing operators to optimize representation geometry.

\section{Limitations}

\begin{itemize}
	\item Only MLPs tested
	\item Low dataset complexity (MNIST, Fashion-MNIST)
	\item Recurrence parameters not exhaustively swept
	\item No theoretical guarantee of generalization
\end{itemize}

\section{Reproducibility}

Code available at:\\ \texttt{https://github.com/urmt/SGP-Tribe3}

All experiments reproducible via provided scripts.

\section{Phase 10: Training Dynamics and Causality}

\subsection{Phase 10A: Training Trajectory}

Training over epochs revealed a strong inverse relationship between Fertility (F) and accuracy. As accuracy increased from approximately 54 percent to 92 percent, F decreased from approximately 0.81 to 0.49.

\subsection{Phase 10B-10C: Correlation Structure}

Extended experiments (n=20) confirmed:

\begin{itemize}
	\item r(F\_total, Accuracy) = -0.993
	\item r(F\_long, Accuracy) = -0.964
	\item r(F\_short, Accuracy) = +0.583
\end{itemize}

This indicates that long-range recurrence structure is the dominant predictor of model performance.

\subsection{Phase 10D: Intervention Test}

Direct modification of the training objective to encourage or suppress F\_long produced no measurable change in final accuracy.

Result: The correlation between F\_long and accuracy is not causal.

\subsection{Phase 10E: Representation Perturbation}

Post-training perturbations of internal representations produced large changes in F\_long (up to +219 percent) while leaving accuracy unchanged.

Conclusion: Recurrence structure is epiphenomenal.

\subsection{Revised Interpretation}

Recurrence-based observables Phi(S,O) are predictive but not causal. They reflect geometric organization of representations rather than mechanisms that determine performance.

\section{Figures}

Data from Phase 10C training dynamics (20 epochs):

- Accuracy increases from 54 percent to 96.8 percent
- F total decreases from 0.81 to 0.46
- Strong negative correlation: r = -0.993
- F_long vs accuracy: r = -0.964
- F_short vs accuracy: r = +0.583

See empirical\_analysis/neural\_networks/phase10c\_training\_dynamics/results.json for full data.

\section{Conclusion}

We have shown that observability in neural representations is operator-dependent. Recurrence-based metrics provide a quantitative framework for analyzing representation geometry and predicting model performance. Fertility strongly predicts accuracy while Coherence follows a logarithmic relationship with Fertility. Extended modeling with operator properties achieves $R^2 \approx 0.93$.

\paragraph{Causal Clarification}
While Fertility (F) demonstrates strong predictive correlation with model accuracy, Phase 10 experiments show that this relationship is not causal. Direct manipulation of recurrence structure does not alter performance, indicating that Phi(S,O) captures geometric properties of representations rather than the mechanisms that determine generalization.

